d ethnic complexities involved in the operation of the marketplace and examines the resourcefulness of the market women in surviving the various hazards they routinely encounter, from coups d'etat to persistent sabotage of their positions from within.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aKumasi (Ghana) -- Commerce. 0aMarkets -- Ghana -- Kumasi. 0aMarketszGhanazKumasi. 0aWomen merchants -- Ghana -- Kumasi. 0aWomen merchantszGhanazKumasi. 0aWomen, Ashanti -- Ghana -- Kumasi -- Economic conditions. 0aWomen, AshantizGhanazKumasixEconomic conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asurvival, accumulation, west africa, western, african, marketplace, market, womens issues, women, woman, female, feminism, analysis, critical, open air, study, kumasi, ghana, social studies, society, community, dynamics, manufactured, wholesale, fieldwork, research, academic, scholarly, economic, political, gender, ethnic, ethnicity, politics, economy, daily life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226107769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226107769/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles